{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01S1Fmwybv95nEtmZySwttre","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"3433 tests pass, zero failures.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Changes\n\n### Production code fix\n- **`/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/modules/sprint/state.ts`** -- Replaced `yamlPath.substring(0, yamlPath.lastIndexOf('/'))` with `dirname(yamlPath)` for cross-platform correctness. Added `dirname` import.\n\n### Test isolation fixes (preventing sprint-state.json corruption)\n- **`/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/modules/sprint/__tests__/sprint-yaml.test.ts`** -- Rewrote integration tests to use `mkdtempSync` + `process.chdir` isolation instead of writing to the real project directory. Added migration mock. Added 4 new tests: non-standard keys, epics field ignored, missing output dir, YAML write failure resilience.\n- **`/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/modules/sprint/__tests__/state.test.ts`** -- Converted from static `STATE_FILE` + manual `unlinkSync` cleanup to `mkdtempSync` + `process.chdir` isolation. Every `writeStateAtomic` call now writes to a tmpdir, not the real project.\n- **`/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/modules/sprint/__tests__/index.test.ts`** -- Same tmpdir isolation conversion. Added 5 new tests for `generateSprintStatusYaml`, `getStoryStatusesFromState`, `readSprintStatusFromState`, `computeSprintCounts` to bring `index.ts` above 80%.\n\n### Story status\n- **`/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/11-2-sprint-status-yaml-derived-view.md`** -- Status changed from `review` to `verifying`.\n\n### Results\n- 3433 tests pass (was 3424 before, +9 new tests)\n- 96.98% overall coverage (above 90% target)\n- All 129 files above 80% per-file floor\n\n---\n\n## Session Issues\n\n### Bugs found and their severity\n\n- **HIGH: Test filesystem corruption vector** -- `sprint-yaml.test.ts`, `state.test.ts`, and `index.test.ts` all called `writeStateAtomic()` from `process.cwd()` (the project root), which wrote both `sprint-state.json` and `sprint-status.yaml` into the real project directory. This is the exact mechanism that corrupted `sprint-state.json` during development. **FIXED** -- all three test files now use tmpdir isolation.\n- **MEDIUM: Platform-incompatible path handling** -- `writeSprintStatusYaml` used `yamlPath.substring(0, yamlPath.lastIndexOf('/'))` instead of `dirname()`, which would fail on Windows backslash paths. **FIXED**.\n- **MEDIUM: Missing edge case tests** -- No test for non-standard story keys, empty output directory, YAML write failures, or epics field being populated but overridden. **FIXED** -- 4 new tests added.\n\n### Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW priority)\n\n- **LOW: `run.ts` still constructs `sprintStatusPath` for YAML** -- Line 66 builds the path to `sprint-status.yaml` and passes it to `generateRalphPrompt`. The prompt template tells Ralph to read `sprint-status.yaml` for story statuses. Since the file is now auto-generated this still works, but the prompt should eventually direct Ralph to read `sprint-state.json` directly.\n- **LOW: `parseStoryKey` is not exported** -- It's a private function in `state.ts` but could be useful for other modules. Its `[Infinity, Infinity]` fallback means non-matching keys sort to the end of the YAML, which is acceptable but implicit.\n- **LOW: `yamlStatus()` only maps `ready` to `ready-for-dev`** -- If new statuses are added to `StoryStatus`, they'll pass through unmapped. No exhaustiveness check.\n\n### Coverage gaps\n\n- None below floor. All 129 files above 80%. Overall 96.98%.\n- Integration test gap: no test verifies that `updateStoryStatus()` -> `writeStateAtomic()` -> `writeSprintStatusYaml()` produces a YAML file with the correct content end-to-end through the full call chain (only tested via `writeStateAtomic` directly).\n\n### Architecture concerns\n\n- `writeSprintStatusYaml` is a synchronous side effect inside `writeStateAtomic`. If YAML generation becomes slow (large state), it will block the state write path. Currently acceptable given typical state sizes.\n- The `readSprintStatusFromState()` function in `index.ts` reads the full state and extracts statuses every time. For hot paths (5-second polling in `run.ts`), this is redundant but cheap.\n\n### Items sent back for re-development\n\n- None. All HIGH and MEDIUM issues fixed. Coverage passes."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a237027b6be396fdb (use SendMessage with to: 'a237027b6be396fdb' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 97466\ntool_uses: 43\nduration_ms: 381087</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bd5543f6-f408-4218-88bd-6e3bcdc37563","uuid":"e302ca0f-007f-43ef-a55c-407e19a25512","timestamp":"2026-03-24T11:18:51.588Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /bmad-code-review for the story at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/11-2-sprint-status-yaml-derived-view.md — perform adversarial review, fix all HIGH and MEDIUM issues found. After fixing, run `codeharness coverage --min-file 80` and ensure all files pass the per-file floor and the overall 90% target. Update the story status to `verifying` when all issues are fixed and coverage passes. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nIMPORTANT CONTEXT: The dev agent corrupted sprint-state.json during development by calling writeStateAtomic() which now auto-generates sprint-status.yaml. The files have been restored. Be especially vigilant about:\n1. Whether writeStateAtomic() side effects are properly isolated in tests (no real filesystem writes)\n2. Whether the YAML generation handles edge cases (empty state, missing epics field, etc.)\n3. Whether sprint-state.json corruption can happen again through normal code paths\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Bugs found and their se