{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012FdvDCJtJ9zADCR3z8WCec","type":"tool_result","content":"   399→\n   400→## 4. What Went Wrong\n   401→\n   402→- **Verification required two attempts.** The first attempt failed because the proof document format was wrong. The verification agent wasted time producing incorrectly formatted proof, then had to study the parser internals to understand the expected format. Better documentation of the proof format would prevent this.\n   403→- **Docker is still down.** Session 10's \"Fix Now\" action item (start Docker Desktop) was not addressed. The workaround worked for 10-3 but story 10-4 (Rust) may need Docker for integration-level verification.\n   404→- **State file discrepancy persisted.** Session 10 noted that `sprint-state.json` and `sprint-status.yaml` disagreed on 10-3 status. The verification agent updated `sprint-state.json` to `done` but the root cause -- no atomic state update between the two files -- remains.\n   405→\n   406→---\n   407→\n   408→## 5. Lessons Learned\n   409→\n   410→### Repeat\n   411→- **Using verification-tier metadata to skip infrastructure requirements.** The `<!-- verification-tier: unit-testable -->` tag saved this session. Stories with all `cli-verifiable` ACs should always use this pattern.\n   412→- **Studying parser expectations before producing formatted output.** The second verification attempt succeeded because the agent read `validateProofQuality()` first. Agents should always check format expectations before generating structured output.\n   413→\n   414→### Avoid\n   415→- **Generating proof documents without checking the expected format first.** The wasted first attempt was entirely avoidable. The proof format should either be documented in the story template or the verification agent should always read `src/modules/verify/proof.ts` before generating proof.\n   416→- **Leaving infrastructure blockers unresolved between sessions.** Docker was flagged as \"Fix Now\" in session 10 but not fixed. Action items marked \"Fix Now\" should be treated as prerequisites for the next session.\n   417→\n   418→---\n   419→\n   420→## 6. Action Items\n   421→\n   422→### Fix Now (Before Next Session)\n   423→1. **Start Docker Desktop.** Carried forward from session 10. Required for any story needing `stack start` or integration tests.\n   424→2. **Document proof format expectations.** Either add format docs to the verification template or add better error messages to `validateProofQuality()` so agents do not have to reverse-engineer the parser.\n   425→\n   426→### Fix Soon (Next Sprint / Next Session)\n   427→1. **Complete story 10-4 (RustProvider).** Next in Epic 10 sequence. Last provider implementation before consumer migration.\n   428→2. **Consider splitting story 10-5** before starting it. It accumulates: type reconciliation (CoverageToolInfo, OtlpResult), consumer migration, branch cleanup, StackDetection dedup. At least 4 sub-stories.\n   429→3. **Auto-update AGENTS.md when new source files are added.** Either a pre-commit hook or a harness-run post-dev step. Manual maintenance is failing.\n   430→4. **Add verification-tier awareness to harness-run pipeline.** Stories tagged `<!-- verification-tier: unit-testable -->` should automatically skip Docker checks. This was the root cause of session 10's blocker.\n   431→\n   432→### Backlog (Track But Not Urgent)\n   433→1. **`hasPythonDep` hyphen/underscore normalization** -- PEP 503 compliance. Low real-world impact with current package set.\n   434→2. **`installOtlp` success path integration test** -- Needs real pip/pipx. Only feasible in Docker/CI.\n   435→3. **Replace TOML regex with proper parser** -- If Python provider usage expands beyond `getProjectName()`.\n   436→4. **Story 15-4: Fix pre-existing TS compilation errors** -- ~50 errors as of session 9. Growing noise.\n   437→5. **Proof parser error messages** -- `validateProofQuality()` should explain what format it expects when validation fails.\n   438→6. All items from sessions 8-10 backlog remain open (15-2/15-5, StackDetection dedup, double detection, recoverCorruptedState test, `_resetRegistry` export cleanup, `readTextSafe` catch branch, `registry.ts` 94.73% coverage).\n   439→\n   440→---\n   441→\n   442→## Cross-Session Summary (Sessions 8-11, 2026-03-24)\n   443→\n   444→### Stories completed today: 3\n   445→- **10-1-stackprovider-interface-and-registry** -- done (session 8)\n   446→- **10-2-nodejs-provider** -- done (session 9)\n   447→- **10-3-python-provider** -- done (sessions 10-11)\n   448→\n   449→### Cumulative stats\n   450→- Tests: 3098 -> 3329 (+231 new tests)\n   451→- Bugs caught by code review: 15 (7 in session 8, 4 in session 9, 4 in session 10) -- all fixed\n   452→- Bugs shipped: 0\n   453→- Stories blocked: 0 (10-3 blocker resolved)\n   454→- Tech debt items deferred: 8 (type mismatches x2, regex fragility x2, comment matching, task markers, consumer branches, AGENTS.md staleness)\n   455→\n   456→### Sprint velocity\n   457→- Epic 10 progress: 0/5 -> 3/5 in one day\n   458→- Pipeline throughput: ~1 story per ralph session (consistent across all 4 sessions)\n   459→- Estimated sessions remaining for Epic 10: 2 (10-4 + 10-5, assuming 10-5 is not split)\n   460→\n   461→---\n   462→\n   463→# Session Retrospective — 2026-03-24 (Sessions 12-13)\n   464→\n   465→**Sprint:** Operational Excellence (Architecture v3 Migration phase)\n   466→**Sessions:** 12 (10-4 full pipeline) and 13 (10-5 story creation + 10-4 verification)\n   467→**Session start:** ~09:14 UTC\n   468→**Appended:** 2026-03-24T13:11Z\n   469→\n   470→---\n   471→\n   472→## 1. Session Summary\n   473→\n   474→| Story | Epic | Outcome | Pipeline Stages Completed |\n   475→|-------|------|---------|---------------------------|\n   476→| 10-4-rust-provider | Epic 10 (Stack Provider Pattern) | done | create-story, dev-story, code-review, verification (implicit via commit) |\n   477→| 10-5-migrate-consumers-to-stackprovider | Epic 10 (Stack Provider Pattern) | ready-for-dev | create-story only |\n   478→\n   479→**Session 12 (~09:14-09:34Z):** Story 10-4 went through the full pipeline -- create-story, dev-story (55 new tests, 3397 total, 0 regressions), and code-review (2 MEDIUM fixed, 2 LOW deferred). Committed as `fa47c33`.\n   480→\n   481→**Session 13 (~09:43Z):** Story 10-5 had its create-story stage completed. The story creation agent expanded the backlog item into a detailed 17-AC spec covering consumer migration for all files that contain stack string comparisons. Story status moved from `backlog` to `ready-for-dev`.\n   482→\n   483→**Net progress:** Epic 10 now has 4 of 5 stories done (10-1, 10-2, 10-3, 10-4). Only 10-5 (consumer migration) remains, at `ready-for-dev`.\n   484→\n   485→---\n   486→\n   487→## 2. Issues Analysis\n   488→\n   489→### Bugs Discovered During Implementation or Verification\n   490→\n   491→| Severity | Story | Issue | Fixed? |\n   492→|----------|-------|-------|--------|\n   493→| MEDIUM | 10-4 | Misleading JSDoc in `hasCargoDep` -- example was backwards | Yes |\n   494→| MEDIUM | 10-4 | Missing false-positive prevention tests for crate substring matching -- 2 tests added | Yes |\n   495→\n   496→Code review caught 2 MEDIUM issues, both fixed in-session. No HIGH-severity bugs this time -- the Rust provider had a cleaner implementation compared to Node.js and Python providers.\n   497→\n   498→### Workarounds Applied (Tech Debt Introduced)\n   499→\n   500→1. **`hasCargoDep` matches commented-out dependencies.** Pre-existing behavior inherited from the pattern used in `stack-detect.ts` and other providers. LOW severity, consistent with the same issue in Python and Node.js providers.\n   501→2. **`getCargoDepsSection` doesn't handle `[dependencies.foo]` subsection format.** TOML allows `[dependencies.foo]` as an alternative to inline table syntax. The current regex only handles the `[dependencies]` section block. Pre-existing limitation, not introduced by this story.\n   502→3. **Bevy system libs detection deferred.** Story notes mention Bevy detection for Docker system libs, but no such logic exists in `dockerfile-template.ts`. Correctly deferred to avoid scope creep.\n   503→\n   504→### Code Quality Concerns\n   505→\n   506→1. **Coverage gap: no integration test for `installOtlp` success path.** Requires `cargo` binary. Same pattern as Python provider's `pip`/`pipx` gap. Consistent limitation across all providers.\n   507→2. **`AppType` union lacks `'library'` variant.** Epic definition mentioned it for Rust, but actual code only has `'generic'`. Story creation agent correctly followed the code, not the aspirational epic text.\n   508→\n   509→### Verification Gaps\n   510→\n   511→- **10-4 verification was implicit.** The story was committed with all tests passing (55 new, 3397 total, 0 regressions). Sprint-status shows `done`. However, the session issues log does not record a formal verification stage for 10-4 -- the review stage at 09:34Z was the last recorded pipeline step.\n   512→- **10-5 create-story flagged 3 risks** that the dev agent should watch for:\n   513→  - AC17 (`verify-prompt.ts`) compares `AppType` not `StackName` -- could cause false positives in boundary tests\n   514→  - AC16 (`teardown.ts`) accesses state field not local variable -- migration needs state shape understanding\n   515→  - `detectAppType()` export chain may break if `stack-detect.ts` deleted before re-export verified\n   516→\n   517→### Tooling/Infrastructure Problems\n   518→\n   519→- No sandbox, permission, or CLI issues reported in these sessions.\n   520→- Docker Desktop status remains unknown (not tested in 10-4 since all 27 ACs are `cli-verifiable`).\n   521→\n   522→---\n   523→\n   524→## 3. What Went Well\n   525→\n   526→- **10-4 completed cleanly.** 55 new tests, zero regressions, 2 review issues (both MEDIUM, both fixed). The cleanest provider implementation across all four (10-1 through 10-4).\n   527→- **All 27 ACs verified as `cli-verifiable`.** No Docker dependency needed. The verification-tier pattern from session 11 is now standard.\n   528→- **Story creation agent handled ambiguity well.** Three points of ambiguity in the epic definition (library AppType, Bevy detection, workspace ordering) were all resolved correctly by following the actual codebase rather than aspirational epic text.\n   529→- **Epic 10 at 80% completion.** Four of five stories done in sessions 8-13. The StackProvider pattern (interface + registry + Node.js + Python + Rust) is fully implemented.\n   530→- **Test suite continues to grow.** 3098 -> 3397 (+299 new tests across sessions 8-13). Zero regressions throughout.\n   531→- **10-5 story spec is thorough.** 17 ACs covering every consumer file, with boundary tests (AC12-13) to enforce zero stack string comparisons outside `src/lib/stacks/`. This gives the dev agent strong guidance for the final migration.\n   532→\n   533→---\n   534→\n   535→## 4. What Went Wrong\n   536→\n   537→- **10-4 lacks a formal verification record.** The session issues log shows dev-story at 09:24Z with no issues and code-review at 09:34Z, but no explicit verification stage. Sprint-status shows `done`, so verification must have happened, but there is no proof document or verification log entry. This is a process gap.\n   538→- **Comment-matching in dependency detection is now tech debt across all three providers.** `hasCargoDep`, `hasPythonDep`, and the Node.js equivalent all match package names inside comments. This was flagged as LOW in each review and deferred each time. It is now a systematic issue, not an isolated one.\n   539→- **Story 10-5 is accumulating scope from all prior sessions.** It now owns: consumer migration for 8+ files, type reconciliation (CoverageToolInfo, OtlpResult), stack-detect.ts deletion, import migration for 7+ test files, boundary test creation, and the `StackDetection` type deduplication. This is the largest story in Epic 10 by far.\n   540→- **`installOtlp` success path is untested in all three providers.** This is a systematic gap -- no provider has integration tests for actual package installation. The gap will persist until a CI/Docker environment is available for integration testing.\n   541→\n   542→---\n   543→\n   544→## 5. Lessons Learned\n   545→\n   546→### Repeat\n   547→- **Following actual code over aspirational epic text.** The story creation agent's decision to use `'generic'` instead of `'library'` for Rust and to defer Bevy detection prevented scope creep and kept the story focused.\n   548→- **Consistent provider implementation pattern.** The Rust provider followed the same structure as Node.js and Python, making it the fastest and cleanest implementation. The pattern is proven.\n   549→- **Expanding minimal story specs before development.** The 10-5 create-story stage produced a 17-AC spec from a backlog item with no detail. This is now standard practice across sessions 8-13.\n   550→\n   551→### Avoid\n   552→- **Systematic deferral of the same issue across stories.** Comment-matching in dependency detection was flagged LOW and deferred in 10-2, 10-3, and 10-4. Three deferrals of the same issue should trigger a tracked fix, not another deferral.\n   553→- **Skipping formal verification for stories that \"obviously pass.\"** Even when all tests pass and code review is clean, the verification stage should produce a record. Story 10-4 has no verification artifact.\n   554→\n   555→---\n   556→\n   557→## 6. Action Items\n   558→\n   559→### Fix Now (Before Next Session)\n   560→1. **Verify that 10-4 proof/verification artifact exists.** If not, document the gap. Do not retroactively create a fake proof.\n   561→\n   562→### Fix Soon (Next Sprint / Next Session)\n   563→1. **Complete story 10-5 (consumer migration).** This is the final story in Epic 10. It is large -- consider whether it can be completed in a single session or needs splitting.\n   564→2. **Evaluate splitting 10-5.** Carried forward from sessions 9-11. The story now has at least 5 distinct concerns: (a) consumer file migration, (b) test file import migration, (c) stack-detect.ts deletion, (d) type reconciliation (CoverageToolInfo, OtlpResult), (e) boundary test creation. Consider splitting into 2-3 sub-stories if the dev agent struggles.\n   565→3. **Address the 10-5 risks flagged by create-story.** The `verify-prompt.ts` AppType vs StackName distinction, `teardown.ts` state field access, and `detectAppType()` export chain all need careful handling during implementation.\n   566→4. **Fix comment-matching in dependency detection.** This is now a systematic issue across all providers. Create a single fix that adds comment-awareness to `hasCargoDep`, `hasPythonDep`, and the Node.js equivalent. Track as a backlog item at minimum.\n   567→\n   568→### Backlog (Track But Not Urgent)\n   569→1. **`installOtlp` integration tests for all providers.** Requires Docker/CI. Systematic gap across Node.js, Python, Rust.\n   570→2. **`getCargoDepsSection` `[dependencies.foo]` subsection format.** TOML edge case, low real-world impact.\n   571→3. **Add `'library'` to `AppType` union.** If Rust library projects need distinct treatment in the future.\n   572→4. **Story 15-4: Fix pre-existing TS compilation errors.** Still at ~50 errors. Noise is chronic.\n   573→5. All items from sessions 8-11 backlog remain open (15-2/15-5, StackDetection dedup, double detection, recoverCorruptedState test, `_resetRegistry` export cleanup, readTextSafe catch branch, registry.ts 94.73%, hasPythonDep normalization, TOML regex replacement, proof parser docs).\n   574→\n   575→---\n   576→\n   577→## Cross-Session Summary (Sessions 8-13, 2026-03-24)\n   578→\n   579→### Stories completed today: 4\n   580→- **10-1-stackprovider-interface-and-registry** -- done (session 8)\n   581→- **10-2-nodejs-provider** -- done (session 9)\n   582→- **10-3-python-provider** -- done (sessions 10-11)\n   583→- **10-4-rust-provider** -- done (sessions 12-13)\n   584→\n   585→### Stories started: 1\n   586→- **10-5-migrate-consumers-to-stackprovider** -- ready-for-dev (story created in session 13)\n   587→\n   588→### Cumulative stats\n   589→- Tests: 3098 -> 3397 (+299 new tests)\n   590→- Bugs caught by code review: 17 (7 in session 8, 4 in session 9, 4 in session 10, 2 in sessions 12-13) -- all fixed\n   591→- Bugs shipped: 0\n   592→- Stories blocked: 0\n   593→- Tech debt items deferred: 11 (type mismatches x2, regex fragility x3, comment matching x3, task markers, consumer branches, AGENTS.md staleness)\n   594→\n   595→### Sprint velocity\n   596→- Epic 10 progress: 0/5 -> 4/5 in one day (6 sessions)\n   597→- Pipeline throughput: ~1 story per ralph session (consistent across all 6 sessions)\n   598→- Estimated sessions remaining for Epic 10: 1 (10-5 only, but it is the largest story)"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01YXPK1TUxfRUPgh7Zdq99k3","session_id":"bd5543f6-f408-4218-88bd-6e3bcdc37563","uuid":"18bfb4ea-8341-416c-ab34-022518ea4494","timestamp":"2026-03-24T11:25:48.727Z"}
